english:
  title: Record of the Cloud Brocade Tower
  author: Lee Jae-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The finest scenic views need not dwell only in remote and distant lands. Even in the capital where the sovereign rules and ten thousand souls converge, mountains and waters are naturally present. Yet those who chase fame in court and profit in marketplace see nothing, though Heng and Lu mountains, Dongting's waters, and the Xiao-Xiang streams lay within a single footstep's view. Why? Because he who hunts the deer sees not the mountain; he who grasps for gold sees not the man; he who discerns the finest autumn hair yet cannot see the cart's full load of kindling. When the heart commits to one thing, the eyes have no leisure for another.

    Those of refined taste and ample means traverse far barriers to claim their rustic retreats, priding themselves humble philosophers. Yet to refrain from such pretense is greater still than practicing it.

    South of the capital lies a pond, a hundred acres in expanse. Around it cluster the common dwellings of ordinary folk, their roofs scaled like fish, their eaves combed tight together. Those who pass—carrying, leading, riding, walking—flow in endless procession. How could they know of the secluded and wondrous realm hidden within their midst?

    In the summer of the Ding-Chou year, when lotus blossoms opened in splendid profusion, Lord Kwon of Hyonbok beheld them with such love that he purchased land directly east of the pond and raised a tower. Eight spans in height, nine spans in width—without foundation stones, yet the pillars endure; without roof tiles, yet the thatch keeps dry; unhewn logs, neither too thick nor too thin; unwashed walls, neither garish nor mean. Behold! The entire pond of lotuses becomes framed within it.

    He then invited his honored father, brothers, and kinfolk to feast upon the tower, spending days in joy and laughter, forgetting to return. His son, skilled in calligraphy, was summoned to inscribe two characters—*Cloud Brocade*—and these became the tower's name.

    When I visited, red fragrance and green shadows filled the boundless waters, where wind-scattered dew danced upon the misty waves. Truly the name was not given in vain! Moreover, the peaks of Dragon Mountain gather their blues and greens beneath the eaves, each dawn and dusk revealing different countenances. The humble dwellings opposite, their rooflines twisted and varied, can be counted from a seated position. Those who pass—running, resting, glancing, calling, conversing with companions, bowing to elders—none can hide their forms, yet remain objects of distant pleasure.

    To those below, only the pond exists; they know not of the tower. How could they know of the people within? Thus scenic beauty need not hide in remote wilderness—it dwells in places the hearts and eyes of court and marketplace habitually overlook. Perhaps heaven creates and earth conceals, unwilling to reveal too freely.

    Though Lord Kwon bears the insignia of a thousand households and wields the power of imperial kinship, his years have not yet reached the vigor of antiquity's prime. He might surrender to luxury and dream in wealth's embrace. Yet he delights in what the benevolent and wise delight in—in mountains and waters—neither startling the common folk nor drawing censure from scholars, while claiming this secluded, wondrous, leisured vastness unknown to marketplace and court. He brings joy to his parents that extends to guests; he enjoys his own being that extends to others. This is truly worthy of praise.

    Ekjae the Recluse records this.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Ding-Chou year' refers to 1337 CE, the sixth year of King Chungsuk's reign in Goryeo.
    - References to Heng and Lu mountains, Dongting Lake, and the Xiao-Xiang streams represent classical China's most celebrated landscapes, invoking the scholarly ideal of mountain retreat.
    - Yixie (益齋), meaning 'Benefit Studio,' is Lee Jae-hyeon's pen name as a recluse.
    - The tower's name 'Cloud Brocade' (雲錦) evokes the shimmering interplay of clouds and lotus blooms reflected in water—fleeting beauty rendered permanent in art.
